4 Further amend said bill, Page 2, Section 590.010, Line 32, by inserting after all of said section
5 and line the following:
6
7 "590.1065. 1. A peace officer shall intervene to prevent or stop another peace officer
8 from using physical force that exceeds the degree of force permitted under this chapter in
9 pursuance of the other peace officer's law enforcement duties in carrying out an arrest of any
10 person, placing any person under detention, taking any person into custody, booking any person,
11 or in the process of crowd or riot control without regard to chain of command.
12 2. A peace officer who intervenes as required under subsection 1 of this section shall
13 report the intervention to his or her immediate supervisor. At a minimum, the report required
14 under this subsection shall include:
15 (1) The date, time, and place of the occurrence;
16 (2) The identity, if known, and description of the participants; and
17 (3) A description of the intervention actions taken.
18
19 Such report shall be made in writing within ten days of the occurrence of the use of such force
20 and shall be appended to all other reports of the incident.
21 3. A member of a law enforcement agency shall not discipline or retaliate in any way
22 against a peace officer for intervening as required under subsection 1 of this section, reporting
23 unconstitutional conduct, or failing to follow what the peace officer reasonably believes is an
24 unconstitutional directive.
25 4. When an internal investigation finds that a peace officer failed to intervene or prevent
26 the use of unlawful physical force under this section, such finding shall be presented to the
27 prosecuting attorney for a determination as to whether charges should be filed. However,
28 nothing in this subsection prohibits the prosecuting attorney from charging a peace officer with
29 failure to intervene before the conclusion of any internal investigation.
30 5. In addition to any criminal liability and penalty, when an internal investigation finds
31 that a peace officer failed to intervene or prevent the use of unlawful physical force under this
32 section in an incident resulting in serious bodily injury or death to any person, the peace officer's
33 employer shall subject the peace officer to discipline, up to and including termination, to the
34 extent permitted under applicable constitutional and statutory law, and the director shall revoke
35 the peace officer's license under chapter 590 upon receipt of notice of the peace officer's
36 discipline. Such revocation may be overturned only if the peace officer is exonerated by a court.
Page 2 of 4

4736H02.03H
1 6. In a case in which the prosecution charges a peace officer with offenses related to and
2 based on the use of excessive force but does not file charges against any other peace officer or
3 officers who were at the scene during the use of such force, the prosecuting attorney shall
4 prepare a written report explaining his or her basis for the decision not to charge any other peace
5 officer with criminal conduct and shall disclose the report to the public; except that, if disclosure
6 of the report would substantially interfere with or jeopardize an ongoing criminal investigation,
7 the prosecuting attorney may delay public disclosure for up to forty-five days. The prosecuting
8 attorney shall post the written report on the prosecuting attorney office's website or, if the office
9 does not have a website, make it publicly available upon request.
10 7. The offense of failing to intervene to prevent the use of unlawful force under this
11 section is considered an act of complicity and the penalty for such act shall be equal to the
12 penalty imposed against the peace officer who committed the original wrongdoing for which the
13 peace officer failed to intervene. Nothing in this subsection shall prohibit or discourage
14 prosecution of any other criminal offense related to failure to intervene, including a higher
15 charge, if supported by the evidence.
16 590.1250. The provisions of sections 590.1250 to 590.1256 shall be known and may be
17 cited as the "Law Enforcement Accountability Act".
18 590.1252. 1. All peace officers in this state shall wear a video camera affixed to the
19 peace officer's uniform while on duty. The video camera shall record each interaction between a
20 peace officer and a member of the public. The recording shall include both audio and video.
21 2. Law enforcement agencies shall preserve any recordings made by a video camera
22 under this section for a minimum of sixty days and make such recordings available to the public
23 through a statewide database within fourteen days of any incident.
24 3. The provisions of this section shall not apply to detectives or other peace officers
25 while they are working in an undercover capacity or to any peace officer in any situation where
26 the wearing of such a video camera would endanger the safety of the officer or the public.
27 4. Law enforcement agencies shall develop policies and procedures necessary to execute
28 the provisions of this section prior to January 1, 2027.
29 5. The director of the department of public safety may promulgate all necessary rules
30 and regulations for the administration of this section. Any rule or portion of a rule, as that term
31 is defined in section 536.010, that is created under the authority delegated in this section shall
32 become effective only if it complies with and is subject to all of the provisions of chapter 536
33 and, if applicable, section 536.028. This section and chapter 536 are nonseverable, and if any of
34 the powers vested with the general assembly pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay the
35 effective date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are subsequently held unconstitutional, then the
36 grant of rulemaking authority and any rule proposed or adopted after August 28, 2026, shall be
37 invalid and void.
38 590.1256. Notwithstanding any other provision of law, if any peace officer is convicted
Page 3 of 4

4736H02.03H
1 of or pleads guilty or nolo contendere to a crime involving the unlawful use or threatened use of
2 physical force, or is found civilly liable for the use of unlawful physical force, the director shall
3 revoke the peace officer's license under this chapter. The director shall not reinstate the peace
4 officer's license or grant a new license to the peace officer unless the peace officer is exonerated
5 by a court."; and
6
7 Further amend said bill by amending the title, enacting clause, and intersectional references
8 accordingly.
